[/asy]

Since $\overline{AB}\parallel\overline{CD}$, we have $\angle B + \angle C = 180^\circ$.  Since $\overline{AD}\parallel\overline{BC}$, we have $\angle A + \angle D = 180^\circ$.  Hence, $\angle C = 180^\circ - \angle B$ and $\angle D = 180^\circ - \angle A$.

Since $\angle A = 62^\circ$, we have $\angle D = 180^\circ - 62^\circ = 118^\circ$.

Since $\angle ADB = 75^\circ$, we have $\angle B = \angle ADB = 75^\circ$.  (Angle $\angle ADB$ is a vertical angle with $\angle B$, so they are in fact the same angle.)

Hence, $\angle C = 180^\circ - 75^\circ = 105^\circ$.

Since $\angle BDC$ is an interior angle of $\triangle BCD$, we have $\angle BDC = \angle C - \angle D = 105^\circ - 118^\circ = \boxed{-13^\circ}$.
The answer is $\boxed{-13}$.

