dot("$O$", O, E);
[/asy]

By the Dandelin-Poncelet Porism, $PF_1 + PF_2 = QF_1 + QF_2 = 2a = 14,$ so $PF_1 = 14 - PF_2.$

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $PF_1F_2,$
\[PF_1^2 = F_1F_2^2 + PF_2^2 - 2 \cdot F_1F_2 \cdot PF_2 \cdot \cos \angle F_1PF_2.\]Since $F_1F_2 = 8$ and $\cos \angle F_1PF_2 = \cos 60^\circ = \frac{1}{2},$ this becomes
\[PF_1^2 = 64 + PF_2^2 - 8PF_2.\]Hence, $(14 - PF_2)^2 = 64 + PF_2^2 - 8PF_2.$  This simplifies to $PF_2 = 10.$

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $F_1PQ,$
\[PQ^2 = PF_1^2 + QF_1^2 - 2 \cdot PF_1 \cdot QF_1 \cdot \cos \angle F_1PQ.\]Since $\cos \angle F_1PQ = \cos 120^\circ = -\frac{1}{2},$ this becomes
\[PQ^2 = (14 - PF_2)^2 + 64 - 2(14 - PF_2) \cdot 8 \cdot \left( -\frac{1}{2} \right).\]Hence,
\[PQ^2 = 196 + 64 - 112 PF_2 + 80 PF_2 = 260 + 80 PF_2.\]Therefore,
\[PQ + F_1Q = PQ + PF_1 = 14 + \sqrt{260 + 80 PF_2}.\]By AM-GM,
\[14 + \sqrt{260 + 80 PF_2} \le 14 + \frac{260 + 80 PF_2}{14} = 14 + \frac{20 + 4PF_2}{2} = 14 + 10 + 2PF_2 = 24 + 2PF_2.\]Equality occurs when $PF_2 = 5,$ or $P = (0,3) + 5 \cdot \langle -\sqrt{3}/2, 1/2 \rangle = \boxed{\left( -\frac{5 \sqrt{3}}{2}, \frac{13}{2} \right)}.$

