Note that $\mathbf{u}$ is a scalar multiple of $\mathbf{v}.$  Since $\mathbf{u}$ lies on the $x$-axis, it must be of the form $\mathbf{u} = \begin{pmatrix} t \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}.$  Then
\[\mathbf{u} \cdot \mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} t \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} = t(1) + 0(2) + 0(2) = t,\]so
\[\|\mathbf{u}\| = |\mathbf{u} \cdot \mathbf{v}| = |t| = \|\mathbf{v}\| \cos \arccos \frac{1}{3} = \frac{\|\mathbf{v}\|}{3} = \frac{\sqrt{1^2 + 2^2 + 2^2}}{3} = \frac{3}{3} = 1.\]Hence, $t = \pm 1.$  We take $t = -1,$ so $\mathbf{u} = \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}.$

Also, $\mathbf{w}$ is the reflection of $\mathbf{v}$ in the plane perpendicular to $\mathbf{u}.$  In other words, $\mathbf{w}$ is the vector such that $\mathbf{w} - \mathbf{v}$ is orthogonal to $\mathbf{u},$ and $\mathbf{w}$ is equidistant from $\mathbf{v}$ and $\mathbf{u}.$

