Note that $\mathbf{p} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix},$ and
\[\|\mathbf{p}\| = 2 = \|\mathbf{v}\| \cos \theta,\]so $\cos \theta = \frac{1}{2}.$  Then
\[\sin^2 \theta = 1 - \cos^2 \theta = \frac{3}{4},\]so $\sin \theta = \pm \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}.$

Also, $\mathbf{v} - \mathbf{p} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 4 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix},$ so
\[\|\mathbf{v} - \mathbf{p}\| = 4 \sqrt{2} = \|\mathbf{v}\| \sin \theta = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}.\]Hence, $\sin \theta = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}.$

Also, the rotation takes $\mathbf{v}$ to a vector in the plane $y = x,$ since the largest projection of the rotated vector on the x-axis is 6.  So, the rotation takes $\mathbf{v}$ to the vector
\[\mathbf{w} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -2 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}.\]Note that this vector has magnitude 6, as desired.
